   "source": [
    "## 2. Dataset Selection and Justification\n",
    "\n",
    "This project uses the Hotel Reservations Dataset, selected from the set of candidate datasets provided for this assignment. The dataset contains transactional booking records including reservation details, customer behavior indicators, pricing information, and cancellation outcomes.\n",
    "\n",
    "Predicting booking cancellations represents a well-defined binary classification problem. Although situated within a hospitality setting, the task exemplifies a broader category of behavioral prediction problems, where past customer activity and contextual features are used to estimate future outcomes. The target variable, booking_status, clearly distinguishes between two classes, Canceled and Not_Canceled, making the dataset directly compatible with supervised classification algorithms.\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset includes both numerical features such as lead time, pricing, and historical bookings, as well as categorical features such as market segment, meal plan, and room type. Cancellations represent approximately one-third of observations. While imbalance exists, it is not extreme, allowing robust evaluation without mandatory resampling techniques. With over 36,000 observations, the dataset supports reliable train-test splitting and cross-validation.\n",
    "\n",
    "Despite its suitability, several limitations must be acknowledged. The dataset originates from a specific hospitality context and may not generalize to other industries or geographic regions. Segmentation variables may reflect historical pricing or operational policies rather than purely behavioral patterns. The dataset does not include explicit demographic attributes, limiting deeper fairness analysis across sensitive demographic dimensions. These limitations are considered when interpreting model performance."
   ]
