    "### 6.3 Outlier Handling via Quantile-Based Clipping \n",
    "\n",
    "Hotel booking data naturally contains extreme but valid values, particularly for variables such as lead time, average room price, and total number of nights. These observations represent rare booking behavior rather than data errors. However, extreme values can have a disproportionate impact on models that rely on distances or are sensitive to scale, especially linear models.\n",
    "\n",
    "Instead of removing entire rows, which would reduce the sample size and potentially affect the class distribution, a conservative clipping strategy is applied. For each numerical feature, the 1st and 99th percentiles are computed using the training data. Values outside this range are clipped to the corresponding bounds. The same thresholds are then applied unchanged to the test set to ensure consistency and prevent data leakage.\n",
    "\n",
    "Before applying clipping, an IQR-based summary is generated for documentation purposes. This step quantifies the number of observations that fall outside the standard 1.5×IQR range for each numerical feature. The summary confirms that extreme values are concentrated in a limited subset of variables. A visual comparison using boxplots illustrates that clipping compresses extreme tails while leaving the central distribution largely unaffected.\n",
    "\n",
    "This approach reduces the influence of extreme values without discarding potentially meaningful observations. It improves numerical stability while preserving the overall data structure and works well in combination with the subsequent scaling procedure.\n",
    "\n",
    "The code first separates numerical and categorical features based on the training set. An IQR-based diagnostic is then computed for each numerical variable to document the presence of extreme values. Clipping thresholds are subsequently learned from the 1st and 99th percentiles of the training data. These bounds are applied to both the training and test sets, ensuring that the transformation remains leakage-free. Finally, boxplots are generated for the features with the highest number of detected outliers to visually verify the effect of clipping."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
