   "source": [
    "Figure 6.1 presents a side-by-side comparison of selected numerical features before and after quantile-based clipping. Each column corresponds to one feature: `avg_price_per_room`, `lead_time`, `no_of_special_requests`, and `total_nights`. Within each column, two boxplots are shown. The left boxplot represents the distribution before clipping, and the right boxplot represents the distribution after clipping.\n",
    "\n",
    "Each boxplot summarizes the distribution of a feature in the training set. The central line inside the box indicates the median. The box itself represents the interquartile range (IQR), which contains the middle 50% of observations. The whiskers extend to values within 1.5 times the IQR, and individual points beyond the whiskers represent extreme observations.\n",
    "\n",
    "The comparison shows that clipping primarily affects the upper tails of highly skewed variables such as `lead_time`, `avg_price_per_room`, and `total_nights`. Extreme values visible in the \"before\" plots are compressed in the \"after\" plots, while the central distribution (median and IQR) remains largely unchanged. This indicates that the procedure reduces the influence of extreme values without substantially altering the overall structure of the data.\n",
    "\n",
    "In contrast, variables with naturally bounded ranges, such as `no_of_special_requests`, show only minor changes, confirming that clipping mainly impacts features with heavy tails.\n"
