   "source": [
    "### 6.4 Encoding and Scaling within a Unified Preprocessing Pipeline\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset includes both numerical and categorical variables, while the selected machine learning models require purely numerical input. Therefore, categorical features must be converted into a numeric representation before model training. In this project, one-hot encoding is applied to all categorical variables. Each category level is represented as a separate binary feature, which preserves the nominal structure of variables such as room type or market segment without introducing artificial ordering. This encoding strategy ensures compatibility with both linear models and tree-based methods and keeps feature effects interpretable.\n",
    "\n",
    "For numerical features, RobustScaler is used instead of StandardScaler or MinMaxScaler. StandardScaler relies on the mean and standard deviation and can be strongly affected by extreme values. MinMaxScaler, on the other hand, may compress most observations into a narrow range when heavy tails are present. Since exploratory analysis revealed right-skewed distributions in variables such as `lead_time` and `avg_price_per_room`, robust scaling provides a more stable transformation. By scaling features based on the median and interquartile range, it reduces the impact of extreme values while preserving the relative structure of the central distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "Encoding and scaling are implemented jointly within a `ColumnTransformer`. The transformer is fitted only on the training data, and the learned parameters are then applied unchanged to the test set. This prevents data leakage and ensures that evaluation remains unbiased. The resulting transformed feature matrices are used consistently across all models so that performance differences reflect algorithmic behavior rather than differences in preprocessing."
   ]
