    "### 6.7 Feature Relevance Assessment Using Mutual Information\n",
    "\n",
    "To obtain a model-independent view of feature relevance, mutual information (MI) is computed between each preprocessed feature and the target variable. Unlike simple correlation measures, mutual information captures both linear and non-linear dependencies. This is particularly useful in the present setting, where cancellation behavior is unlikely to follow purely linear patterns. For example, lead time or price-related variables may exhibit threshold effects or non-linear relationships with the cancellation outcome.\n",
    "\n",
    "Mutual information provides an estimate of how much knowing a feature reduces uncertainty about the target. Higher values indicate stronger statistical dependence, while values close to zero suggest limited individual predictive signal. It is important to note, however, that MI evaluates each feature independently and does not capture interaction effects between variables.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this project, mutual information is used as a diagnostic tool rather than a strict feature selection criterion. The goal is to better understand how predictive signal is distributed across the feature space and to support interpretation of model behavior. No features are removed solely based on their MI scores, ensuring that potentially useful interactions remain available to the learning algorithms."
